# Reviews of surface energy balance models.
@article{liu2016regional,
  title={Regional estimation of remotely sensed evapotranspiration using the surface energy balance-advection (SEB-A) method},
  author={Liu, Suhua and Su, Hongbo and Zhang, Renhua and Tian, Jing and Chen, Shaohui and Wang, Weizhen},
  journal={Remote Sensing},
  volume={8},
  number={8},
  pages={644},
  year={2016},
  publisher={MDPI}
}
Liu, S. et al. 2016. Regional estimation of remotely sensed evapotranspiration using the Surface Energy Balance-Advection (SEB-A) method. Remote Sensing, 8, 644.
They  state that both single- and two-source SEB models used with remote sensing are “founded on the premise of ignoring the energy transported by horizontal advection,” and that horizontal advection is a major contributor to surface-energy-balance uncertainty.
- Partition ET into a “local” energy-balance component and an “exotic” (advective) component.
- Opens by noting that classical SEB models ignore horizontal advection and that this is a key reason for non-closure of the surface energy balance over heterogeneous, irrigated landscapes.
- Show that horizontal advection is often the primary reason for energy-balance non-closure, and quantify how large the “exotic” ET term can be in irrigated areas.
% both single- and two-source SEB models used with remote sensing are founded on the premise of ignoring the energy transported by horizontal advection, and that horizontal advection is a major contributor to surface-energy-balance uncertainty


