@article{wang2024advection,
  title={How advection affects the surface energy balance and its closure at an irrigated alfalfa field},
  author={Wang, Tianxin and Alfieri, Joseph and Mallick, Kanishka and Arias-Ortiz, Ariane and Anderson, Martha and Fisher, Joshua B and Girotto, Manuela and Szutu, Daphne and Verfaillie, Joseph and Baldocchi, Dennis},
  journal={Agricultural and Forest Meteorology},
  volume={357},
  pages={110196},
  year={2024},
  publisher={Elsevier}
}
Using high-resolution thermal imagery (ECOSTRESS, Landsat) and multi-tower flux measurements, this study shows that advection is more common than previously expected, and that including advective fluxes improves energy-balance closure from 89 % to 97 %. 
They argue that their results provide insights for algorithms that may improve remote sensing ET products that treat pixels as isolated columns rather than also considering the lateral effects of heat and moisture transport.
Wang et al. 2024 (irrigated alfalfa + ECOSTRESS)
- Question + Todo: Do they propose a method to implement/operationalize results? How much energy does that 8% correspond to.  Look at lit review surrounding Figure 1, how local and non-local advection is distinguished.  Email Joe about this paper. 

Including measured advective fluxes (horizontal advection + vertical flux divergence) improves energy-balance closure from 89% to 97% over 37 days (quantifies how much energy you miss if you ignore advective terms).
At this site advective terms are on the order of ~8% of the surface energy budget on average (sometimes larger), and they describe λE at the anchor tower as enhanced by both local and non-local advection.


