At the Niwot Ridge AmeriFlux site (Colorado, USA; high-elevation subalpine forest),
\citet{yi2008contribution} used a multi-tower approach to estimate horizontal and
vertical advective CO$_2$ fluxes and showed that advection can contribute
substantially to NEE during stable conditions. They also noted that instantaneous
advective estimates can reach unrealistically large magnitudes under some conditions,
highlighting sensitivity to measurement errors in mean winds and concentration
gradients. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

To enable a site-to-site comparison with consistent instrumentation and geometry,
\citet{feigenwinter2008comparison} conducted coordinated 3-D multi-tower experiments
at three CarboEurope forest sites spanning different terrain (Renon/Ritten, Italian Alps;
Wetzstein, Germany; Norunda, Sweden). They reported that both horizontal and vertical
advective terms can be comparable to turbulent fluxes at night, but that the sign and
magnitude vary strongly with wind direction and stability, and that uncertainties in
wind vectors and scalar gradients often dominate the advection error budget. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

Finally, \citet{etzold2010contribution} evaluated advection corrections for a steep
mountain-slope forest site in Switzerland (CH-Lae, L\"ageren) during the growing season,
contrasting a ``physical'' correction using measured advection terms with the standard
$u_*$-filter approach. They found that advection can materially affect the inferred carbon
budget at complex-terrain sites, while also underscoring the practical difficulty of
obtaining sufficiently accurate mean-flow and concentration fields to support routine
advection correction. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

From an ET perspective, these studies matter less for carbon per se than for the
\emph{meteorological regimes} they diagnose: stable stratification, drainage/recirculation
flows, and sharp scalar gradients that create strong mean advective transports. The same
flow structures can advect sensible heat and water vapour, motivating process-based
approaches that diagnose advective enhancement from boundary conditions (e.g., $T_s$ and
far-field $T_a, q_a$) rather than relying on direct measurement of advection terms.







